@REM -----------------------------------------------------------------------
@NODE "Project->Icon Save Mode" "Project->Icon Save Mode"
@prev "Project->Icon Type"
@next "Project->NewIcons"
@TOC "Project"
Menu:	@{b}Project@{ub}
Item:	@{b}Icon Save Mode@{ub}

@{b}Function@{ub}
  Controls how an icon image is saved to disk.  There are two sub groups.  One group controls how many graphic planes are stored.  The other determines how the size is calculated.

Planar controls:

o @{b}Current Depth@{ub} - The icon will be saved with the same number of planes that the screen has.

o @{b}Strip Planes@{ub} - The highest valued pixel determines the number of planes.  If the image only uses the first 3 pens, only 2 planes will be saved, regardless of the screen depth.

o @{b}Force Eight@{ub} - All unused planes will be a duplicate of the highest used one.  This is the format used in early versions of MagicWB icons.  This format is the most screen depth resilient, but also the largest in terms of disk space and graphics memory.


Size controls:

o @{b}Auto Size@{ub} - The icon size will be only the area that contains non-zero pixels.

o @{b}Full Size@{ub} - The entire buffer will be saved.

o @{b}Custom Size@{ub} - The area defined with the "Define Area" drawing tool will be saved.

@{b}Notes@{ub}
  Contrary to that mentioned by users earlier, the Strip Planes option does not save visible colors only.  If the icon was originally designed with more planes than the current screen has, some pixels will be hidden.  To permantly get rid of these "invisible" pixels, first save the icon using the "Current Depth" option.  Then select "Restore" and save it again using the "Strip Planes" option.
@ENDNODE
